    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and log.csv, parse timestamps as UTC datetimes. Compute global P95 per group (group by cmdb_id and kpi_name for metrics; by cmdb_id and log_name for logs) using each group's full series. Then filter both datasets to the incident window 2024-01-20 22:28:53 to 2024-01-20 22:58:53 UTC. For the allowed service components list ['carts','catalogue','orders','payment','user'], produce a compact table with one row per (cmdb_id, KPI/log name) showing: data_source (metric or log), cmdb_id, name (kpi_name or log_name), total_points (full series), P95, window_points, window_anomaly_count (value >= P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_utc (first timestamp in window where value >= P95 or null), window_max_value. Include only rows where the name contains 'socket' or is 'log.row_count' or 'mem' (to show memory as secondary). Sort by window_anomaly_count desc then window_max_value desc and limit to top 20 rows. Return the resulting table."
}

{
    "analysis": "We followed the prescribed workflow: preprocess (grouping metrics/logs by component-KPI and computing global percentiles on full series), anomaly detection (identifying points in the incident window that exceed P95), fault identification (counting consecutive/aggregate anomalies and recording earliest anomaly times), and root-cause localization (using metrics and logs since traces/error_logs are empty). Key evidence: (1) catalogue.socket shows the strongest and earliest anomaly among allowed services — 20 of 25 samples in the incident window exceed the component's global P95, with the first breach at 2024-01-20 22:36:00 UTC; (2) multiple other infra/kernel socket KPIs (rabbitmq, DBs, queue-master, session-db, rabbitmq-exporter) are simultaneously at-or-above P95, indicating a socket/network-layer problem impacting messaging and DB components; (3) log.row_count spikes (front-end, user, queue-master, catalogue, orders, payment, shipping) occur at ~22:36:00 UTC, coincident with catalogue.socket’s earliest anomaly; (4) diskio anomalies are non-actionable zeros and memory changes are minor and secondary. Traces and error_logs are empty, so we relied on metrics + logs. Considering: the root cause must be one of {carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user}. Among those, catalogue has the largest, earliest, and most sustained socket KPI fault and coincident service-level log row spikes. Therefore the most plausible root-cause component is the catalogue service, and the failure reason is at the socket/network layer (socket error / network connectivity issue) that began around 2024-01-20 22:36:00 UTC.",
    "completed": "True",
    "instruction": "Diagnosis summary: Root-cause service/component = catalogue (service). Failure reason = socket error (network/socket-layer issue impacting service-to-infra connectivity). First observed at 2024-01-20 22:36:00 UTC (incident window 2024-01-20 22:28:53–22:58:53 UTC). Supporting evidence: catalogue.socket breached global P95 on 20/25 window samples (earliest 22:36:00); coincident log.row_count spikes at ~22:36 across catalogue and other front/back-end services; multiple infra socket KPIs (rabbitmq, DBs, queue-master, session-db) are simultaneously at or above P95, consistent with a network/socket-level outage. Recommended next actions: check network connectivity and socket/socket-queue metrics for catalogue (open file/socket limits, network interface errors), inspect catalogue's connections to DB and message queue, and review host-level network interface and firewall/iptables logs around 22:36 UTC. If available, gather packet-level/network device logs and enable trace collection for deeper call-chain localization." }

Review summary: metric analysis showed a sustained, early socket anomaly on the catalogue service (20 of 25 samples in the incident window ≥ its global P95) with the first breach at 2024-01-20 22:36:00 UTC. Log.row_count spikes across front/back-end services occurred at ~22:36 UTC as well. Multiple infra socket KPIs (DBs, RabbitMQ, queue-master) were simultaneously at-or-above P95, consistent with a network/socket-layer problem. Traces and error_logs were empty. Based on the timing, magnitude, and coincidence of service-level socket breaches and log rate spikes, the most likely root cause is a socket error affecting the catalogue service beginning at 2024-01-20 22:36:00 UTC.

